1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.beyond2000.com/images/icons/space.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>There actually was a link to this concept last time I checked. It just had a title which wasn't specific. Here are a few links courtesy of Vishniac.<br><br>Extremely efficient nuclear fuel could take man to Mars in just two weeks.<br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.spaceref.com/news/viewpr.html?pid=3470">www.spaceref.com/news/viewpr.html?pid=3470</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sciam.com/news/010301/IMG/tomars222.GIF"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>Researchers at Ben-Gurion University of the Negev in Israel are suggesting a new way to rocket through space at record speeds: propel your craft using the products of fission reactions in thin metallic films of americium-242m (Am-242m). The approach, described in the December issue of Nuclear Instruments and Methods in Physics Research A, might one day cut the travel time from Earth to Mars down from eight to 10 months to a mere two weeks. <br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.sciam.com/news/010301/1.html">www.sciam.com/news/010301/1.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n0009/10marsbricks/mars.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>A novel type of nuclear reactor could make it possible for spacecraft to travel from the Earth to Mars in as little as two weeks, one Israeli researcher has found. <br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n0101/19marsnuclear/">www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n0101/19marsnuclear/</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.beyond2000.com/images/editorial/2000_07/colony.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>Future journeys to Mars could be made short enough to fit into a Christmas break. The discovery of a time-saving nuclear fuel by Israeli scientists might even see space vehicles speeding between Earth and the Red Planet in as little as two weeks. <br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.beyond2000.com/news/Jan_01/story_953.html">www.beyond2000.com/news/Jan_01/story_953.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.beyond2000.com/images/editorial/1999_12/current.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>I'm going to start a new thread for throwing all our good links into. We desperately need to update and expand upon the links section. It's hopelessly out of date as of this week. We need a links library really. For organisations, such as FAS and ANS etc etc etc. Rocket articles ofcourse. Atomic stuff. Space organisations and news sites. Other messageboards. If we throw our links into a thread they can be simply copied over from one location. <br><br>I'll make a duplicate of this in suggestions.  <br> <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!<br><a href="http://clubs.yahoo.com/clubs/projectorion">PROJECT ORION CLUB</a> <br><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.net/">NUCLEARSPACE.NET</a></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 2/12/02 7:50:48 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 159<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/8/02 7:00:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Links</span